   274	---
   275	
   276	## 4. Package Boundaries
   277	
   278	### Depends on (external)
   279	- Standard TypeScript runtime; no framework dependencies.
   280	- Node.js `EventEmitter` (or equivalent) for internal event bus. No external event library.
   281	
   282	### Depends on (internal)
   283	- Nothing from this monorepo. Core is the dependency root.
   284	
   285	### Depended on by (internal)
   286	- All other `@relay-assistant/*` packages import types from core.
   287	
   288	### Relay foundation boundary
   289	- Core calls into the relay foundation through **adapters**, not directly. Two adapter interfaces are defined in core:
   290	
   291	```typescript
   292	/** Injected by the surfaces layer to push normalized inbound messages into core. */
   293	export interface RelayInboundAdapter {
   294	  onMessage(handler: (message: InboundMessage) => void): void;
   295	  offMessage(handler: (message: InboundMessage) => void): void;
   296	}
   297	
   298	/** Injected by the surfaces layer to deliver outbound events. */
   299	export interface RelayOutboundAdapter {
   300	  /** Targeted send to a single surface. */
   301	  send(event: OutboundEvent): Promise<void>;
   302	  /** Fanout to all attached surfaces of a session. */
   303	  fanout?(event: OutboundEvent, attachedSurfaceIds: string[]): Promise<void>;
   304	}
   305	```
   306	
   307	The surfaces layer implements these interfaces. Core never imports relay packages.
   308	
   309	Note: `fanout` is optional on the interface so that test stubs can implement just `send`. `SurfaceRegistry` implements both.
   310	
   311	---
   312	
   313	## 5. Dependency Rules
   314	
   315	| Direction | Rule |
   316	|---|---|
   317	| Other packages → core | Allowed. Import types and factory functions only. |
   318	| Core → other packages | Forbidden. Core has no runtime imports from this monorepo. |
   319	| Core → relay foundation | Through adapter interfaces only. Core never imports relay packages. |
   320	| Cloud layer → core | Allowed. Cloud layer may wrap or extend, but core must remain functional without it. |

